issue.title: Quantization of T5-XL Model leads to "exceeds maximum protobuf"

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
Hello,

I would like to quantize the T5-XL model (>2GB model size). It is basically the same problem as mentioned in #7017 
There is a nightly solution proposed but I would really appreciate it if this would be supported natively. 
Also mentioned in the above issue, the shape inference was removed in  https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/5210/files, but it seems that this merge was reverted.
 
**Describe the solution you'd like**
In this post https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/PythonAPIOverview.md#shape-inference-a-large-onnx-model-2gb is a currently supported variant of shape inference. So the current implementation of the shape inferences could be to use a try-exception-statement such that if the `onnx.shape_inference.infer_shapes(model)` fails, the `onnx.shape_inference.infer_shapes_path('path/to/the/model.onnx')` could be used. Although this is considered to not be good practice.
Further I am not sure if the shape inference is the only problem for large models.

Thank you.

issue.title: Loss of accuracy when GPT-2 based model is exported to ONNX

labels.name: model:transformer
labels.description: issues related to a transformer model: BERT, GPT2, Hugging Face, Longformer, T5, etc.

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Performance loss**
 - My distilgpt2 model exported from huggingface to ONNX when run in ONNX-Runtime doesn't yield desired accuracy.
 

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution: Linux Ubuntu 20.04
- ONNX Runtime installed from: PyPI 
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.5.2
- Python version: 3.7.9
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): Not applicable
- I tried on CPU, so following are not applicable.
- Driver Version: 460.32.03   
- CUDA Version: 11.2
- GPU model and memory: Quadro RTX 8000


**Details:**
- I have been trying out GPT-2 model for sentence-scoring for correcting sentences which have homophones.
__Example:__ To ensure correct usage of homophones in sentences, I used huggingface's distilgpt2 to see which of ["The bare is in the forest", "The bear is in the forest."] is more probable.
 - For this use-case, I get the outputs from the distilgpt2 model, and take cross-entropy loss between inputs & labels and then consider the sentence from a set of candidate sentences more probable if it has the least loss.
 - While the original huggingface model gives precision, recall and F-0.5 score in the range of 0.90-0.95, the same model when exported to ONNX as shown in [this example notebook](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/1ce2982f65e5516067fdcaef19409279173b0d75/onnxruntime/python/tools/transformers/notebooks/Inference_GPT2_with_OnnxRuntime_on_CPU.ipynb) gives lower precision, recall and F-0.5 scores. F-score drops to around 0.82-0.83. Also, there is about 30% drop in true positives.
 - On further observation, I found that scores between the unconverted HF model and the converted model sometimes vary in the 4th decimal place.
 - Also, observed a similar performance drop earlier when we converted  and used a TokenClassification model from huggingface in ONNX-Runtime.
 - Is this variation the likely cause of this performance drop while scoring sentences with homophones? What can be done to ensure that performance drop is as small as possible? Please mention here if any settings, etc., need to be changed / configured or if I am missing something. Any pointers to resources would be helpful. Thanks.
